Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Remove the @venison leg steaks{2} from your fridge to allow them to come up to room temperature. Bring a large #saucepan{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil for the potatoes. Peel and slice the @potatoes{450} into 1 cm wide rounds. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim the @green beans{80}. Quarter, core and thinly slice the @apple{1}(cored and sliced thinly) (no need to peel).

Once boiling, add the potato slices to the water and simmer until just tender, ~{8-12%minutes}. TIP: The potatoes are cooked when you can easily slip a knife through them. Once cooked, reserve some of the potato cooking water, then carefully drain in a #colander{}. Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%bottle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat. Add half the garlic and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}. Then add the @creme fraiche{150}, @chicken stock paste{10}, @reserved potato water{75} and half the @grated hard Italian style cheese{25}. Mix together, bring to the boil, then remove from the heat. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Lay the cooked potato slices in layers in an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}, then pour over the creamy mixture. Sprinkle the remaining cheese on top. Bake on the top shelf of your oven until golden brown and bubbly, ~{15-20%minutes}. TIP: Put the dish onto a #baking tray{} to catch any drips. Meanwhile, to make the dressing pop the @red wine vinegar{12}, @walnuts{20} and olive oil into a #medium bowl{}. Mix, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} then set aside.

Clean your frying pan and return to medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil. When hot, add the apple slices and stir-fry until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Once cooked, transfer to the bowl of dressing. Pop the (now empty) pan back on medium-high heat. Add the green beans and stir-fry until starting to char, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in the garlic, turn the heat down to medium and cook for ~{1%minute}. Then add a splash of water and immediately cover with a #lid{} or some #foil{}. Allow to cook until the beans are tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Once cooked, transfer the beans to a #small bowl{} and cover to keep warm.

Sprinkle the steaks with salt and the @cracked black pepper{2}, ensuring they are well coated. Return the (now empty) pan to medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil. When hot, lay the steaks into the pan and brown for ~{1%minute} on all sides. Lower the heat slightly and cook for another ~{1%minute} on each side. TIP: Venison is best served rare but if you like it more well done, cook for another 2 mins on each side. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. The venison is safe to eat when the outside is browned. Once cooked, rest the steaks on a #board{} loosely covered with foil.

Once rested, slice the venison steaks widthways and serve on plates with the dauphinoise and green beans alongside. Toss the @pea shoots{40} in the apple and walnut dressing and serve alongside. Enjoy!

> This Pepper Crusted Venison Steak and Dauphinoise Potatoes is a luxurious dinner night option, made with premium ingredients for a real taste of luxury at home!